This guide walks you through everything you need to do before running the main code on your Raspberry Pi. It covers required hardware components, wiring, OS configuration, and all software dependencies. Follow the steps in order, skipping any step is the most common cause of the game failing to start.
Materials:
Hardware Requirements:
Component	Specification	Purpose
Raspberry Pi 4 Model B	2 GB or 4 GB RAM	Main processing unit — runs the game loop, sensor I/O, and signal processing
MPU6050 IMU Module	6-DoF (GY-521 breakout)	Provides accelerometer + gyroscope tilt data via I2C
Female-to-Female Jumper Wires	4 wires minimum	Connect MPU6050 pins to Raspberry Pi GPIO header
MicroSD Card	16 GB+ Class 10 / A1	Holds Raspberry Pi OS, Python, game files, and libraries
USB-C Power Adapter	5V / 3A (official Pi PSU)	Stable power — underpowered supplies cause random crashes during gameplay
HDMI Monitor	Any resolution (micro-HDMI cable)	Display for the racing game — required since pygame needs a screen
USB Keyboard + Mouse	Any USB/wireless	Initial setup, terminal commands, and keyboard fallback for the game
Micro-HDMI to HDMI Cable	Pi 4 uses micro-HDMI	Connect Raspberry Pi to the monitor

MPU6050 Wiring:
MPU6050 Pin	Raspberry Pi Pin	GPIO Name	Notes
VCC	Pin 1	3.3V Power	 3.3V ONLY — never connect to Pin 2 (5V)
GND	Pin 6	Ground	Any GND pin works (6, 9, 14, 20, 25, 30, 34, 39)
SDA	Pin 3	GPIO 2 (SDA1)	I2C data line — must be this exact pin
SCL	Pin 5	GPIO 3 (SCL1)	I2C clock line — must be this exact pin

GPIO Pin Reference Diagram:
Function	Pin Name	Pin #	Pin #	Pin Name	Function	Notes
VCC → MPU6050	3.3V PWR	1	2	5V PWR	DO NOT USE	Connect MPU6050 VCC to Pin 1 (3.3V), never Pin 2 (5V)
SDA → MPU6050	GPIO 2 (SDA)	3	4	5V PWR	—	Connect MPU6050 SDA to Pin 3
SCL → MPU6050	GPIO 3 (SCL)	5	6	Ground	GND → MPU6050	Connect MPU6050 GND to Pin 6

Enable I2C & Verify Sensor:
I2C is disabled by default on Raspberry Pi OS. The game cannot communicate with the MPU6050 until I2C is enabled and the Pi is rebooted.

•	Enable I2C via raspi-config
1.	Open a terminal on the Raspberry Pi.
2.	Run the configuration tool:
 
$ sudo raspi-config
 
3.	Navigate to:  Interface Options  →  I2C  →  Enable  →  Yes  →  Finish
4.	Reboot the Pi when prompted, or manually run:
 
$ sudo reboot
 

•	3.2  Verify the MPU6050 is Detected
After rebooting, confirm the sensor appears at I2C address 0x68:

 
# Scan the I2C bus
$ sudo i2cdetect -y 1
 

Expected output: You should see  68  printed in the grid at row 60, column 8. If the entire grid shows dashes (--), recheck your wiring.

 
