Software Installation:
There are two ways to do this. 
Install all required system and Python packages in the order shown below. An active internet connection is required.

1.	Update the OS
Always update before installing packages to avoid version conflicts:


$ sudo apt-get update
$ sudo apt-get upgrade -y


2.	 Install System Packages
These system-level packages provide I2C support and the tools needed to verify the sensor. Do not skip this step — smbus2 depends on the kernel I2C drivers installed here.


3.	$ sudo apt-get install python3-smbus i2c-tools python3-pip -y


Package	Why it is needed
python3-smbus	Provides the kernel-level SMBus/I2C driver bindings for Python
i2c-tools	Provides i2cdetect and other utilities to verify the sensor is wired correctly
python3-pip	Python package manager — needed to install smbus2 and pygame

4.	Install Python Libraries
Install the two required Python packages:

# Required: direct I2C communication with MPU6050
$ pip3 install smbus2

# Required: game rendering and input handling
$ pip3 install pygame


Python Package	Version Tested	Purpose
smbus2	0.4.3	Communicates with the MPU6050 at register level over I2C — replaces the broken mpu6050 pip package entirely
pygame	2.5.2	Renders the racing game window, handles 60 FPS game loop, draws road/car/obstacles, and provides keyboard fallback controls
math	stdlib	Built into Python — provides atan2() for accelerometer angle calculation inside the complementary filter

5.	Verify Installations
Confirm both libraries are correctly installed:


$ python3 -c "import smbus2; print('smbus2 OK')"
$ python3 -c "import pygame; print('pygame OK')"


Both commands should print OK. If either says  ModuleNotFoundError , re-run the pip3 install command from Step 4.3.
	The other way is to do this on your raspberry pi command prompt.
1.	Type ls -a to show all of the projects
2.	Then type cd “name of file”
3.	After type ls- a again.
4.	Try doing pip3 install mpu6050-raspberrypi
5.	If it says “error: externally-managed environment”
6.	Do this :
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate
pip install “name of the file”-raspberrypi pygame
7.	Then after installing try running:
pip freeze > requirements.txt
ls-a
8.	It should show a venv on the right side
9.	Run the code.
Testing the mpu6050 sensors:
1.	Copy the mpu6050_sensor_test
2.	Run it
3.	If you tilt the mpu6050 and it changes numbers your tilt sensor is ready.
Running the Game File:
1.	Copy the main code
2.	Run it
3.	If the display shows the game and you try to run it, you’re done and finished.

